{
  "texts": [
    "It remains possible, in terms introduced by Dennett (1991), to see the structures in events that rationalising explanation hook onto and explicate as \"real patterns\" in a natural world that does not contain any irreducible mindedness or intentionality.",
    "Such world-involving agent-centred patterns are, as much as the bare bodily movements at their core, a scientific explanandum that invites modelling of its causal structure.",
    "While we might use our own capacities to understand and respond to the signs of practical rationality where we encounter them as a heuristic tool, this does not mean we have to afford these phenomena any special status.",
    "We therefore needn't doubt that they can be explained and described using the methods of mainstream cognitive science; and no special metaphysical story needs to be told about how agency and cognition 'emerges' from their elements.",
    "19 In other words, the Anscombean proposal is compatible with a reductionist picture of the relation between patterns and the entities that make them up, so long as the reduction doesn't run via a unified agency-constituting cognitive mechanism (cf."
  ]
}